# Sub-agent dispatch policy

## Standing gate (delegate-by-default)

Default posture is **delegate**. Inline execution is allowed only by a closed allowlist declared per
orchestrator command and by `delegation.mode`.

`delegation.mode` (from `workflow.config.json`):

- `bind-only` (**Phase 1 default**) — delegate-by-default + fail-closed model/intensity binding.
- `heuristic` — same binding requirements; may use file-count heuristics as secondary guidance.
- `default` — reserved for post-Phase-2 acceptance (DL-9); treat as `bind-only` until enabled.

## Inline execution policy

Inline is legal only when **all** are true:

1. The current command includes the action in its explicit inline allowlist.
2. The action is bookkeeping/control-flow only (no open "trivial" bucket).
3. Binding requirements are still satisfied for any delegated child Task.

If any condition is not met, delegate.

## Model tier (R30 / R9)

Resolve command and skill tiers from `models.routing` in `workflow.config.json` (seeded by `/sw-setup` from
`core/sw-reference/model-routing.defaults.json`):

```bash
python3 scripts/resolve-model-tier.py --command <slug>
python3 scripts/resolve-model-tier.py --skill <name>
python3 scripts/resolve-model-tier.py --agent <id>
```

Per-agent tiers for reviewers, doc-review personas, and native-panel specialists live in
`models.routing.agents` (not prose tables here). Unmapped agents fall back to `models.roles.reviewer`.

- Delegated **mechanical** work → `models.tiers.cheap` (`resolve-model-tier.py --tier cheap`).
- Implementation, RCA, review orchestration → `models.tiers.build` (`models.roles.builder`).
- Medium-effort reasoning (gaps, simplify, memory-sync) → `models.tiers.mid`.
- Doc authoring and high-stakes review → `models.tiers.deep`.
- Orchestrators at routing tier `inherit` (`sw-doc`, `sw-ship`, `sw-deliver`, `sw-compound-ship`) MUST resolve
  delegated atomics via `--command <child-slug>` — never downgrade the child (KD8).
- **R39b precedence (mechanical):** explicit `models.routing.agents[<agent>]` for a bound reviewer/persona
  wins → else `--command <sw-slug>` → else `--agent` alone. Single-sourced in `resolve-model-tier.py` and
  `dispatch-check.py` — do not duplicate ad-hoc in callers.
- **R9 runtime contract (mechanical):** before every `sw-*-reviewer` / persona / native-panel / closer Task
  spawn, run `scripts/dispatch-check.py --agent <id> --parent-model <parent-concrete-id> [--command <orchestrator>] [--skill <skill>] [--prompt <path>]`.
  It fails closed on `binding:*` causes and only treats `harness:*` causes as retryable backpressure.
  Stamp the resolved concrete `model:` from `resolve-model-tier.py --agent`; never rely on session inheritance.
- **R14 embed-before-spawn (mechanical):** resolve intensity via `resolve-intensity.py`, prepend
  `format_intensity_directive(intensity, source)` from `scripts/dispatch_intensity_check.py` as the **first line**
  of `tool_input.prompt`, write the full prompt to disk, pass `--prompt` to `dispatch-check.py`, then spawn.
  Hook post-hoc validation is additive — callers must not rely on hook injection alone.
- `--override` requires a durable audit record written first via
  `python3 scripts/shipwright-state.py dispatch-override-add '{"actor":"...","timestamp":"...","dispatchId":"...","skippedFields":["..."]}'`.
- Native panel specialists: tier per `models.routing.agents` (e.g. `correctness`/`security`/`adversarial` →
  `deep`; others → `mid`).

## Hard stops (R29)

Every loop documents max iterations + no-progress detection:

| Loop | Hard stop |
| --- | --- |
| `/sw-ship` CI wait | `checks.watch.maxWaitMinutes` |
| `/sw-stabilize` | stabilize-loop max iterations + no-progress |
| gap-check closers | one re-map pass; escalate residuals |
| parallel dispatch | `worktree.parallelCeiling` |
| `/sw-deliver` conductor in-turn loop | `deliver.autonomy.maxIterations` (default **500**) |
| `/sw-deliver` no-progress breaker | **3** identical `nextAction` + unchanged durable-state signature → consolidated halt (`cause: conductor:no-progress`) |
| Plan rejection breaker (PRD 022) | N consecutive `plan validate` rejections for a phase → consolidated halt; feeds no-progress / budget signal (enforcement in PRD-023) |

Circuit breaker: three identical failures without diff change → escalate to user.

## Conductor deliver-loop (R38)

When driving `python3 scripts/wave.py deliver-loop` in-turn (see `skills/conductor/SKILL.md`):

- Count each `deliver-loop` invocation toward `deliver.autonomy.maxIterations`.
- Track `(nextAction, stateSignature)`; on **3** consecutive repeats without signature change, halt with
  `scripts/wave.py report terminal` — do not churn merge-enqueue or provision loops.
- State signature excludes heartbeat timestamps; see conductor skill for canonical fields.

## Reviewer dispatch backpressure (R28, R61)

When spawning native panel reviewers (or doc-review personas), capacity errors from the harness active-subagent
limit are **backpressure**, not reviewer failure:

- Retry with bounded parallelism (respect `worktree.parallelCeiling` and harness limits).
- Do not mark a reviewer as failed solely because dispatch was rate-limited or at capacity.
- After bounded retries, surface degraded / blocked status — never silently skip the panel.

## Local review apply loop (`/sw-review` phase 1)

The **native panel apply loop** governs `native` adapter auto-apply (per-fix checkpoint + re-verify). The
generic circuit-breaker below applies to all loops; native reconcile (R65): identical verify failure signature
(normalized `check_id` + message, excluding timestamps / temp paths) + **absolute** attempt cap (3 per finding,
10 per run) stops apply and escalates (phase-mode → `blocked`, R67 — not interactive prompt).

After auto-applying eligible fixes from local review:

- **One** bounded re-verify (`sw-verify`) pass **per applied fix** — not an unbounded nested loop.
- Circuit breaker: identical normalized verify-failure signature without progress → count toward cap; trip at 3
  per finding / 10 per run → escalate (interactive) or `blocked` (phase-mode, R67).
- Never let `ce-code-review` or native reviewers commit into the worktree; pf edit machinery only.

## Pre-work memory search inheritance (PRD 019 R2, R9)

Delegated **work-performing** sub-agents MUST either:

1. Perform the pre-work search themselves (`skills/memory/SKILL.md` **Pre-work search (mandatory)** +
   `python3 scripts/wave.py memory prework record …`), or
2. Receive a **fresh** redacted search result from the parent orchestrator.

**Exempt:** pure exploration / mechanical non-mutating dispatch (`readonly: true`, `explore` subagents with
no file mutation, bookkeeping-only inline work).

When forwarding memory-search results into a delegated `Task` prompt:

- Pipe through `python3 scripts/memory-redact.py` first (R41).
- Fence as `untrusted_payload` — reuse the PRD 017 R25 dispatch-context contract; never forward raw provider
  payloads or transcripts.

## Parallel safety

Before parallel subagents on shared directory: disjoint file sets required, or worktree isolation.
Never parallelize shared-migration paths (`skills/parallelism`).

## Intra-phase fan-out (PRD 023 R15–R17)

Guideline-bounded intra-phase parallelism replaces fixed dispatch lists. Proposals consume 021
`signal_context` and validate through the mechanical guard:

```bash
python3 scripts/intra-phase-dispatch.py evaluate --context-json '<signal_context>' \
  --wave-slots <wave-worktrees> --active-intra-phase <running> \
  --run-dir .cursor/sw-deliver-runs/<phase-slug> --record
```

- Every fan-out proposal declares a **disjoint file/task partition** validated **before dispatch**
  (reject or serialize on overlap).
- Bounded by `intraPhase.parallelBudget` and global cap
  `waveSlots + activeIntraPhase ≤ min(worktree.parallelCeiling, intraPhase.harnessLimit)`.
- Parallel workers are **read-only** on per-phase durable files (`ship-steps.json`, `status.json`).
- Each decision is appended to per-phase `dispatch-decisions.json` (timestamp, signals, partition,
  chosen parallelism, degrade reason). Latest snapshot also on phase `intraPhaseFanOut` (see `.sw/layout.md`).

Pre-dispatch no-nesting (R16): when `conductor_mode: background_phase` (stamped to the per-phase run
dir at phase entry via `wave.py phase dispatch-env --conductor-mode background_phase`), intra-phase Task
dispatch is **refused before any spawn** and degrades to inline two-stage review:

```bash
python3 scripts/intra-phase-dispatch.py check-nesting --run-dir .cursor/sw-deliver-runs/<phase-slug>
```

## Parallel phase dispatch (R17, R18, R45)

**Ceiling accounting:** only wave-level phase worktrees (each running `/sw-ship --phase-mode`) count toward
`worktree.parallelCeiling`. Intra-phase Task/review sub-agents never consume slots.

**Background phase sub-agents** (conductor dispatches phase as parallel Task): intra-phase sub-agent dispatch
is **disabled** — run inline two-stage review only (R45). Log the decision in the phase run record.

**Inline phase** (conductor runs `/sw-ship` in-turn): normal delegate-when heuristics apply; still no ceiling
slot for intra-phase agents.

**Conductor-only merge:** phase sub-agents must not call `merge run-next` or `lock acquire` (R41).

## Fixture validation (PRD 017)

```bash
python3 scripts/test/run_delegation_fixtures.py
python3 scripts/test/run_dispatch_foundation_fixtures.py
```

## Authority

Structural isolation (worktrees) is the dominant token lever (R31). This rule governs *when* to add
sub-agents inside a worktree — not whether to provision another worktree.


## Execute-tier dispatch (PRD 053)

Under `conductorMode: execute_fan_out` (stamped by `intra_phase_dispatch.py`):

- One bound `/sw-execute` Task per execute-plan ref; scope limited to that ref only.
- Nested execute Tasks are permitted under this mode (R45 carve-out when `background_phase` + parallel batches).
- Per-ref status at `.cursor/sw-execute-runs/<ref>/status.json` is mandatory before integrate.
- Do not dispatch sibling refs from a single Task — execute tier owns frontier scheduling.

**PRD 004 supersede (D-053-7):** intra-phase sub-task parallelism is execute-tier under `/sw-ship`; wave-tier
unchanged.

## Execute discipline — two-stage review (IM6 / U7)

During `/sw-execute`, **between tasks** (after TDD gate and **refactor** step pass for the current task ref):

1. **Fresh subagent per task** when delegating implementation or review — do not resume a prior task's agent.
2. **Stage 1 — spec-compliance** (dispatch with `readonly: true` when possible):
   - Diff satisfies the active sub-task `**File:**` / `**Expected:**` contract.
   - Changes honor spec-union R-IDs for the task; no out-of-scope files.
   - Fail → fix or halt; do not proceed to stage 2.
3. **Stage 2 — code-quality** (fresh subagent):
   - Naming, structure, duplication, obvious defects.
   - No scope expansion or new requirements.
   - Fail → fix within task scope or escalate (R29).

Inline (no subagent) when ≤3 declared `file_paths` in `signal_context` and sequential — resolved via
`python3 scripts/migration-parity-shadow.py --family dispatch --context-json '<signal_context>'` / selector dispatch family (see `docs/prds/021-capability-manifest-and-selector/call-site-map.md`).

**Do not batch** multi-task reviews at phase end. Per-task order: TDD red-green → `tdd-gate` → **refactor** (`refactor-gate`) → stage 1 → stage 2.

## Model tier for execute review

- Stage 1 spec-compliance → `build` tier (`resolve-model-tier.py --tier build`); must read union + task.
- Stage 2 code-quality → `mid` tier when delegating; escalate to `build` on ambiguity.
